attribute.name: exponentWeight
attribute.description:
The averaging weight factor used by the RED drop mechanism.
The weight factor is used when calculating the average queue length and it is represented as the parameter n in the following formula:
average_queue_length = old_average_queue_length * (1 - 2^-n) + current_queue_length * 2^-n, where 2^-n means: 2 raised to the power of –n.
The averaging weight factor controls the sensitivity to bursts and rapid changes in the current queue length. Setting the averaging weight factor too high causes the average queue length to respond too slowly to changes in the current queue size, thus not reacting to congestion. Setting the averaging weight factor too low causes the average queue length to respond too fast to changes in the actual queue size, thus overreacting to bursts and dropping packets unnecessarily.
Guideline: The egress bandwidth and the average packet size should influence the choice of this attribute value.

attribute.name: maxThreshold
attribute.description:
The maximum threshold for RED.
When the average queue length is above the minimum threshold, RED starts dropping packets. The rate of packet drop increases linearly as the average queue length increases until the average queue length reaches the maximum threshold.
When the average queue length is above the maximum threshold, all packets are dropped.

attribute.name: minThreshold
attribute.description:
The minimum threshold for RED.
When the average queue length is above the minimum threshold, RED starts dropping packets. The rate of packet drop increases linearly as the average queue length increases until the average queue length reaches the maximum threshold.
When the average queue length is above the maximum threshold, all packets are dropped.
attribute.dependencies: minThreshold should be less than or equal to maxThreshold.

class.name: QueueSystem
class.description:
Quality of Service (QoS) queue system.
Bandwidth and sizes (burst sizes, queue sizes) include the complete Ethernet frame.
Dependencies: Must have one child element.

validationRules.rule: <schema xmlns="http://purl.oclc.org/dsdl/schematron"> <pattern> <rule> <assert test='(count(QueueTailDrop) + count(QueueRed) + count(SchedulerSp) + count(SchedulerDwrr) + count(Shaper)) eq 1'> <value-of select="."/> Must have one child element </assert> <assert test='every $order in concatenate(QueueTailDrop/@order, concatenate(QueueRed/@order, concatenate(SchedulerSp/@order, concatenate(SchedulerDwrr/@order, Shaper/@order)))) satisfies $order eq 0'> <value-of select="."/> Attribute order of child to QueueSystem must be 0 </assert> </rule> </pattern> </schema>

class.name: SchedulerDwrr
class.description: Deficit Weighted Round Robin (DWRR) scheduler. In the hierarchical QoS context, a scheduler can directly contain multiple queues and schedulers as its children, to construct the hierarchical tree.

validationRules.rule: <schema xmlns="http://purl.oclc.org/dsdl/schematron"> <pattern> <rule> <assert test='(count(QueueTailDrop) + count(QueueRed) + count(SchedulerSp) + count(SchedulerDwrr) + count(Shaper) eq count(@schedulingWeight))'> <value-of select="."/> Number of weights does not match number of children </assert> <assert test='every $order in concatenate(QueueTailDrop/@order, concatenate(QueueRed/@order, concatenate(SchedulerSp/@order, concatenate(SchedulerDwrr/@order, Shaper/@order)))) satisfies count(QueueTailDrop) + count(QueueRed) + count(SchedulerSp) + count(SchedulerDwrr) + count(Shaper) gt $order'> <value-of select="."/> Attribute order has too high value for child</assert> <assert test='are-distinct-values(concatenate(QueueTailDrop/@order, concatenate(QueueRed/@order, concatenate(SchedulerSp/@order, concatenate(SchedulerDwrr/@order, Shaper/@order)))))'> <value-of select="."/> Attribute order of children are not unique </assert> </rule> </pattern> </schema>

class.description: SP (strict priority) scheduler. In hierarchical QoS context, a scheduler is allowed to directly contain multiple queues, and/or schedulers, and/or shapers as its children to construct the hierarchical tree.
